Data from Transect Surveys. N is the North transect comprised of the 90 and 270 degree (magnetic) radials from the radial survey of the North end of Hog Island. T1 etc are the Hog Island research transects.

Transects 1, 2, 4, 5 and beach profiles of 3. For each transect elevations andÂ  distance from the steel post transect marker nearest the ocean. Elevations are relative to the high water line on day when the
data was collected. Terry has the dates in the field notes if they are not available in the data. This data has been reformatted for easy incorporation into the database.

Elevation Surveys of Hog Island, VA Transects in 1989
Transects T1 through T5 run from beach to marsh across Hog Island, from a steel post driven into the dune line.
T3 was surveyed but the markers were washed away before GPS could be use to mark its location.Â
The N survey goes east-west rather than at right angles to the island shoreline.Â

Distance from the primary survey monument for each transect. Note that negative numbers are used to indicate direction along the transect, because the survey monument was located in the middle of the transect.
ELEVATION - Elevation relative high water line

Serial number of CeraDiver sensor used.
Note for barometric pressure sensor this is air temperature inside a closed container exposed to the sun.
Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer

Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm. The reference barometer is located in Phillips Creek Marsh, between 30-40 km away from the stations.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.
Water depth relative to mean sea level
WATERMSL - Water depth relative to mean sea level

Wells were surveyed in using GPS and optical levels relative to NAVD-88 which is assumed to approximate mean sea level for this marsh. If no level information is available for a well, this value will be set to missing.
Depth of water relative to the marsh surface
WATERSURFACE - Depth of water relative to the marsh surface
PRESFLAG - Water pressure data quality flag

Spikes are single values that exceed the preceding and following values by 30 millibars or more. Valid pressure ranges are considered to fall between 860 and 1500 millibar. If a flag is set, no derived variables will be calculated based on the pressure.

Spikes are rapid increases or decreases in temperature that are more than 10 degrees C. Valid ranges for temperatures are between -35 degrees Celsius and 45 degrees Celsius. Note that the temperature of the reference barometer may exceed these values due to its location in a closed box exposed to the sun.

The Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project, in association with the Virginia Marine Resources Commission, conducted an intensive GPS survey during February 1992. A second GPS survey was conducted in August 1994 to add supplemental GPS monuments. Most monuments consist of stainless steel pipes driven to refusal and topped with a bolt with a point imprinted on it. Others may consist of existing markers or cultural features. Elevations refer to the monument, not the surrounding ground surface. All data were processed by the VCR/LTER. Several caveats must be applied to use of this survey network:
1. These are preliminary results and are subject to change as the network is revised.
2. This network is designed for research purposes only, the data are not suitable for legal uses of survey data.

3. The network includes several US Government benchmarks, but except for the VCR1 monument recently resurveyed and fixed by the National Geodetic Survey (see below), the coordinates for those benchmarks have not been adjusted to agree with blue-book values for those benchmarks.
4. Elevations are based on mean sea-level (NAVD88) for a single point (VCR1). No geoid corrections have been applied to any other point.

Most data were collected using dual-frequency Trimble 4000 GPS units and additional data was collected with single-frequency GPS units. All measurements were made using the WGS84 datum. Each location was measured a minimum of two times with data collection times greater than 3 hours per survey.
1. Data were processed using TRIMVEC+ software.
2. Baselines were computed using widelane fixed solutions whenever possible. If a quality ratio <3 could not be obtained, a float solution was used instead.
3. A network made up of only the highest quality baselines (fixed) solutions was created and fixed based on the geographical coordinates and elevation of the VCR1 monument.

4. A network comprised of all points was compiled. As before, the coordinates for VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) were fixed in 3 dimensions. The stations BROWNSVILLE, FARL and SHUG were fixed to their horizontal coordinates in the high-quality-only network. Network adjustments were then performed on all other points.
NGS location of VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) monument. The VCR1 monument is part of the High Accuracy and Resolution Network (HARN).

5/3/94 - National Geodetic Survey fixes the VCR1 monument at 37-deg, 17-min, 42.15663-seconds North Latitude and 75-deg, 55-min, 59.49256-sec. West Longitude, with an ellipsoidal height of -28.261 m. Geoid height is modeled to be 8.7 m. Horizontal datum is NAD 83 and vertical datum is NAVD 88 (for NGVD 29, add 0.2 m).

In each plot, Zostera marina shoot density was determined by counting individual shoots in situ in 10 0.25 m2 quadrats, and scaling to shoot density m-2. Quadrats were placed at a random distance perpendicular to the transect line at each sampling point.

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

For biomass estimates, three cores (6Ã¢â¬ I.D.) containing shoots were collected, including sediment and seagrass biomass to 15 cm depth, in each plot. The cores were sieved (1 cm mesh size) in situ to remove sediments. In the laboratory, shoots were separated into aboveground and belowground biomass for each core, and the number of shoots was counted to obtain estimates of total, above- and belowground biomass shoot-1. Canopy height was determined as the average height of the 3 tallest leaves.

This dataset contains information on water level and temperature in a series of groundwater wells in Phillips Creek Marsh, near Nassawadox, VA on the Eastern Shore of Virginia. Data on temperature and water pressure are collected every 12 minutes using automated Ceradiver data loggers and transformed following atmospheric adjustment into water levels. This dataset extends previous measurements using different technologies for three of the wells included in dataset: Ground Water Level at Brownsville and Hog Island, VA 1997-2009 (knb-lter-vcr.142). The Creekbank (CB), High Marsh (BH) and Tracy2 sites are the CB1, JUNCUS2 and BW3 sites in this dataset, respectively.

Sediments were collected in 60 cc syringe corers to a depth of 5 cm in each vegetated and bare plot for determination of carbon and nitrogen contents. Five sediment cores were collected in each plot for each analysis; the reported values represent the integrated measure for the 0-5 cm depth interval. Carbon and nitrogen contents were measured on dried sediment (60 ÃÂºC for at least 48 h) using a Carlo Erba Elemental Analyzer with a 1020 ÃÂºC combustion tube and 650 ÃÂºC reduction tube, and helium as a carrier gas.

LiDAR point cloud for Northampton and Accomack Co., VA 2010
Virginia Coast Reserve Long-Term Ecological Research Project
Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Virginia, 291 McCormick Road, PO Box 400123
This dataset contains LiDAR data for Northampton and Accomack Counties on the Eastern Shore of Virginia.

It was created using LiDAR by Sanborn Geosystems under a contract with the Virginia Information Technologies Agency (VITA) with funding from The Nature Conservancy, USGS and the Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project of the University of Virginia.

The LiDAR data is stored in .LAS files with 4 returns per point. Spacing between points is approximately 1 meter. Returns are classified as to whether they are water or land. Each LAS file represents an area 5,000x5,000 feet. A tile index to aid in the identification of which LAS files are needed for a site are also included.
The data are is in the State Plane coordinate system (U.S. Feet) and uses the NAVD88 vertical datum with the 2009 Geoid for elevation in feet.

Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer

Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm. The reference barometer is located in Phillips Creek Marsh, between 30-40 km away from the stations.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.

PRESFLAG - Water pressure data quality flag

Spikes are single values that exceed the preceding and following values by 30 millibars or more. Valid pressure ranges are considered to fall between 860 and 1500 millibar. If a flag is set, no derived variables will be calculated based on the pressure.

Spikes are rapid increases or decreases in temperature that are more than 10 degrees C. Valid ranges for temperatures are between -35 degrees Celsius and 45 degrees Celsius. Note that the temperature of the reference barometer may exceed these values due to its location in a closed box exposed to the sun.

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

In the 1.0 acre and 100,000 seed plots (n = 4), plant productivity was measured on all shoots within a 20 cm x 10 cm anchored grid using the leaf marking method where the blades are punctured with a 22-gauge needle, using the top of the sheath bundle as the reference point. Shoots were collected 10-15 days after marking, and leaf area and dry weights of the older growth (above the scar) and the new growth (below the scar, but excluding the sheath bundle and including new shoots) were measured.

This dataset contains measurements of CO2 and H2O concentrations, temperature and wind speed made every 1/10th of a second.
Important note: due to the high frequency of measurements, this dataset is very large (>25 GB) and may take a long time to download.

The research was conducted at the Virginia Coastal Reserve Long Term Ecological Research (VCR LTER) site on the Eastern Shore of Virginia, USA. The flux tower site (37ÃÂ°24'39.85N, 75ÃÂ°50'0.53W) a lagoonal salt marsh which is located near the area of Fowling point. The site is located at about 2.2 kilometers away from the mainland and 10.7 kilometers away from Hog Island, the nearest barrier island. The flux tower is situated at about 80 meters away from the creek edge, on the lagoonal salt marsh.

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

The flux tower instrumentation includesÂ  an eddy covariance system and various micrometeorological sensors.Â  The eddy covariance system consists of a three dimensional sonic anemometer (model CSAT3, Campbell Scientific Inc, Logan UT, USA), which measures the components of the wind velocity in the x, y, and z directions along with virtual temperature and an open path gas analyzer (model LI-7500, Licor Inc, Lincoln, NE, USA) which measures
the concentration of CO2 and H2O in the air. These measurements were used to estimate the fluxes of carbon dioxide, latent heat, and sensible heat.Â

The construction methodologies were adopted from the previous work of Barr (2005), who described the construction of a flux towerÂ  located at a riverine mangrove forest in the western Florida Everglades.Â  The tower base consists of two platforms, one for the aluminum tower base and the other for the battery bank and electronics. The tower base and the battery platform are 0.61 m and 1.4 m high from the sediment surface, respectively. The platforms are constructed on 11 wooden pilings (4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢x4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢) pressure treated lumber that were sunk into the sediment to a suitable depth for stability (~1.5 m). To ensure equal weight distribution on all 11 tiers and to prevent tiers from settling, pressure treated foundation beams (2x8Ã¢â¬) were bolted to the pilings using galvanized 7xÃÂ½ carriage bolts. Scrap boards of 2x12 treated lumber

were installed around the base of vertical tiers; these planks rest flat on the sediment and provide extra surface area toÂ  prevent foundation beams from sinking. The floor of the tower base and the ancillary platform were constructed with 2Ã¢â¬x8Ã¢â¬ pressure treated planks, which rest on floor beams made up of 2Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ x 4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ pressure treated lumber.
The flux tower was constructed using pre-fabricated aluminum tower sections (Universal towers, Clinton Township, MI, USA). Each section is 3 m long, and two sections

were used in the tower construction giving aÂ  total height of 6.7 m from the soil sediment surface. The tower sections were mounted on an aluminum base (3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3/8Ã¢â¬â¢) that was bolted onto the main platform base. To maintain structural stability, the tower was anchored to the sediment surface using a set of three guy wires attached to the top of the tower. These guy wires were attached to wooden pilings on the ground through galvanized turnbuckles (Model 3000T566, McMaster-Carr, Atlanta, GA, USA). Although two tower sections do not require the use of guy wires, these wereÂ  added for extra stability as theÂ  tower may be exposed to high force winds.Â

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

Five surface sediment samples were collected in each plot to a depth of 1 cm for analysis of benthic chlorophyll. Collected were kept in the dark on ice until they were frozen at -80 oC immediately after returning to the laboratory. Samples were later thawed and extracted in a 45:45 methanol:acetone solution overnight in the freezer after a 1-minute sonication. Benthic chlorophyll was determined spectrophotometrically using the equations of Lorenzen (1967).

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

Current data collection method is to sample the SET sites each spring (late April to early June) and take measurements using the original SET arm at all sites.Â  Current use is with fiberglass pins, which replaced the brass pins of the late 1990s.Â  Sampling is best done at mid to low tides to ensure that the marsh site is not inundated.Â  For access to the sampling point, we use two 8-ft boards and one 10 ft board to provide access for two people to the SET.Â  One person does the measurements, the other records the data on field sheets or field notebook.Â

After the plate is leveled at each of 4 cardinal locations at the SET, the 9 pins are lowered until they just make contact with the marsh surface. Each pin is measured from the plate surface to the top of the pin using a meter stick. Data are recordedÂ to the nearest tenth of a centimeter.
Detailed instructions on data collection and recording from Mike Erwin sent to David Boyd on 2012-06-01:

1. First, we are down to only the four SETs at Wachapreague, labeled CB1E (Curlew Bay East) with a HM high marsh, and a MM mid marsh SET; also the CB2W (Curlew Bay West) - also a HM and a MM SET. At Mockhorn Island WMA, there are two: we have a Mock-E and a Mock-W both of which are considered mid marsh. Gates Bay SET sites were abandoned as we have anomalous readings there.

2. Take one reading per SET in the spring, from late April to late May advised. Low or mid tide levels will ensure that no water is standing at the SETs when you take measurements. Low tide is critical at the CB sites for the mid marsh SETs.
3. Upon approaching each SET from the creek side, avoid stepping within a radius of 4-5 ft. of where the pipe is located.
4. After placing the three boards, place the SET arm in the slots such that the arm position is at the 900 position first, which is the A position. The 1200 position is B, 300 is C, and 600 is D.

5. Make sure the arm is level first before pins are dropped. 6. Lower each pin until it BARELY touches the sediment surface. 7. With meter stick, measure FROM THE PLATE to the top of the pin, recording in tenths of centimeters on the data sheets. 8. After returning to the office, calculate the means for each SET (N=36 pins) and record in the SET master file (Erwin SET file).

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

Current data collection method is to sample the SET sites each spring (late April to early June) and take measurements using the original SET arm at all sites.Â  Current use is with fiberglass pins, which replaced the brass pins of the late 1990s.Â  Sampling is best done at mid to low tides to ensure that the marsh site is not inundated.Â  For access to the sampling point, we use two 8-ft boards and one 10 ft board to provide access for two people to the SET.Â  One person does the measurements, the other records the data on field sheets or field notebook.Â

After the plate is leveled at each of 4 cardinal locations at the SET, the 9 pins are lowered until they just make contact with the marsh surface. Each pin is measured from the plate surface to the top of the pin using a meter stick. Data are recordedÂ to the nearest tenth of a centimeter.
Detailed instructions on data collection and recording from Mike Erwin sent to David Boyd on 2012-06-01:

1. First, we are down to only the four SETs at Wachapreague, labeled CB1E (Curlew Bay East) with a HM high marsh, and a MM mid marsh SET; also the CB2W (Curlew Bay West) - also a HM and a MM SET. At Mockhorn Island WMA, there are two: we have a Mock-E and a Mock-W both of which are considered mid marsh. Gates Bay SET sites were abandoned as we have anomalous readings there.

2. Take one reading per SET in the spring, from late April to late May advised. Low or mid tide levels will ensure that no water is standing at the SETs when you take measurements. Low tide is critical at the CB sites for the mid marsh SETs.
3. Upon approaching each SET from the creek side, avoid stepping within a radius of 4-5 ft. of where the pipe is located.
4. After placing the three boards, place the SET arm in the slots such that the arm position is at the 900 position first, which is the A position. The 1200 position is B, 300 is C, and 600 is D.

5. Make sure the arm is level first before pins are dropped. 6. Lower each pin until it BARELY touches the sediment surface. 7. With meter stick, measure FROM THE PLATE to the top of the pin, recording in tenths of centimeters on the data sheets. 8. After returning to the office, calculate the means for each SET (N=36 pins) and record in the SET master file (Erwin SET file).

Dataset consists of a subset of all the USGS-sponsored data collected using the USGS Patuxent Wildlife Research Center old style SET arm, which began in Fall 1998.Â  Because of changes made to the type of pins used (switched from brass pins to fiberglass in 2002), we present only the post-2002 data here.Â  Each datum under ELEVTN variable is the meanÂ SET elevation measured from 36 pins.

In the Wachapreague marshes, three high marsh sites (short form Spartina alterniflora) were selected (Curlew Bay 1 (East)HM, Curlew Bay 2 (West)HM, and Gates BayHM), and three low-mid marsh sites (tall form Spartina)Â as well (same names, except MM as a suffix).Â  About 20 miles south, at the northÂ end of the Mockhorn Island WildlifeÂ Management Area (state owned), only two low-mid marsh sites were selected - Mockhorn East and West.Â Â The dataset does not include elevations taken at unvegetated pond sites as measurements were curtailed after 2003.Â

Five surface sediment samples were collected in each plot to a depth of 1 cm for analysis of benthic chlorophyll. Collected were kept in the dark on ice until they were frozen at -80 oC immediately after returning to the laboratory. Samples were later thawed and extracted in a 45:45 methanol:acetone solution overnight in the freezer after a 1-minute sonication. Benthic chlorophyll was determined spectrophotometrically using the equations of Lorenzen (1967).

The flux tower instrumentation includesÂ  an eddy covariance system and various micrometeorological sensors.Â  The eddy covariance system consists of a three dimensional sonic anemometer (model CSAT3, Campbell Scientific Inc, Logan UT, USA), which measures the components of the wind velocity in the x, y, and z directions along with virtual temperature and an open path gas analyzer (model LI-7500, Licor Inc, Lincoln, NE, USA) which measures
the concentration of CO2 and H2O in the air. These measurements were used to estimate the fluxes of carbon dioxide, latent heat, and sensible heat.Â

The construction methodologies were adopted from the previous work of Barr (2005), who described the construction of a flux towerÂ  located at a riverine mangrove forest in the western Florida Everglades.Â  The tower base consists of two platforms, one for the aluminum tower base and the other for the battery bank and electronics. The tower base and the battery platform are 0.61 m and 1.4 m high from the sediment surface, respectively. The platforms are constructed on 11 wooden pilings (4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢x4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢) pressure treated lumber that were sunk into the sediment to a suitable depth for stability (~1.5 m). To ensure equal weight distribution on all 11 tiers and to prevent tiers from settling, pressure treated foundation beams (2x8Ã¢â¬) were bolted to the pilings using galvanized 7xÃÂ½ carriage bolts. Scrap boards of 2x12 treated lumber

were installed around the base of vertical tiers; these planks rest flat on the sediment and provide extra surface area toÂ  prevent foundation beams from sinking. The floor of the tower base and the ancillary platform were constructed with 2Ã¢â¬x8Ã¢â¬ pressure treated planks, which rest on floor beams made up of 2Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ x 4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ pressure treated lumber.
The flux tower was constructed using pre-fabricated aluminum tower sections (Universal towers, Clinton Township, MI, USA). Each section is 3 m long, and two sections

were used in the tower construction giving aÂ  total height of 6.7 m from the soil sediment surface. The tower sections were mounted on an aluminum base (3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3/8Ã¢â¬â¢) that was bolted onto the main platform base. To maintain structural stability, the tower was anchored to the sediment surface using a set of three guy wires attached to the top of the tower. These guy wires were attached to wooden pilings on the ground through galvanized turnbuckles (Model 3000T566, McMaster-Carr, Atlanta, GA, USA). Although two tower sections do not require the use of guy wires, these wereÂ  added for extra stability as theÂ  tower may be exposed to high force winds.Â

LiDAR data was analyzed to extract shoreline and dune features to extract points every 10 meters along the shoreline.
ATM 1998, 2005 CHARTS and 2009 ERAL LiDAR data were used. 1997 data used a first-return LiDAR and was only used for shoreline delineation.
Features were defined using definitions from Sallenger, A. H. 2000. Storm impact scale for barrier islands. Journal of Coastal Research 16:890Ã¢â¬â895.ÃÂ

DhighÃÂ  are point features of the position and elevation of the most seaward dune crest (known as Dhigh) derived from the lidar data. If there was no dune crest above 1.5m elev the berm was selected as Dhigh. All Dhigh points were selected from lidar data that was gridded and smoothed into cross-shore profiles every 10m alongshore. The grids are broken up into segments alongshore of similar shoreline orientation. To view the segments open the VA_segments shapefile. With in each segment the cross-shore profiles every 10 m were named profile 1, profile 2, profile 3, etc. That profile value is reflected in the attribute table in the column labeled 'profile'. The lat and lon of each Dhigh point is represented as well as northing and easting. The elevation of the dune crest is in the 'dhigh_z' column. The position of the dune is presented in a few columns. The cross-shore position of the dune is called 'dhigh_x' which refers to meters inland from the position 0. The 0 position is located between the two segment points.

DlowÃÂ  are point features of the position and elevation of the most seaward dune toe (known as Dlow) derived from the lidar data. If there was no dune crest above 1.5m elev the berm was selected as Dhigh and no Dlow exists. All Dlow points were selected from lidar data that was gridded and smoothed into cross-shore profiles every 10m alongshore. The grids are broken up into segments alongshore of similar shoreline orientation. To view the segments open the VA_segments shapefile. With in each segment the cross-shore profiles every 10 m were named profile 1, profile 2, profile 3, etc. That profile value is reflected in the attribute table in the column labeled 'profile'. The lat and lon of each Dlow point is represented as well as northing and easting. The elevation of the dune tow is in the 'dlow_z' column. The position of the dune is presented in a few columns. The cross-shore position of the dune toe is called 'dlow_x' which refers to meters inland from the position 0. The 0 position is located between the two segment points (VA_segments).ÃÂ

Polygons of overwash probability during a hypothetical storm with characteristics similar to Hurricane Bonnie in 1998. The bar to the west is the probability of overwash for the VCR based on 1998 lidar data. The middle bar is the 2005 overwash probability based on the 2005 lidar data. And the most east bar is the 2009 overwash probability to the hypothetical storm. The storm surge used was 1.1m, the significant water wave height was 3.7m and the period was 7s. The probability is in part determined by comparing the relative elevation of the most seaward dune crest (Dhigh) and the maximum wave runup (Rhigh). Dhigh elevations are given in the attribute table. Each elevation value is a mean value representing 100m alongshore. The elevation of the most seaward dune toe (Dlow) also represents mean dlow elevation along the same 100m. R2 is the 2% exceedence elevation the swash will reach during the hypothetical storm. That elevation is added to the surge (1.1m) to equal Rhigh. Then the probability is represented as a % of overwash probability for each 100m segment of beach.

Zip files contain ESRI shapefiles. The name of the file identifies the parameter contained in the file and the year. Dhigh files have the most seaward dune crest. Dlow files have the most seaward dune toe. Shoreline position is mean-high water (0.34 m > mean-sea level).Additionally, the KML.zip file contains graphical representation of overwash probabilities for specific island-year combinations for display in Google Earth.

Dataset consists of a subset of all the USGS-sponsored data collected using the USGS Patuxent Wildlife Research Center old style SET arm, which began in Fall 1998.Â  Because of changes made to the type of pins used (switched from brass pins to fiberglass in 2002), we present only the post-2002 data here.Â  Each datum under ELEVTN variable is the meanÂ SET elevation measured from 36 pins.

In the Wachapreague marshes, three high marsh sites (short form Spartina alterniflora) were selected (Curlew Bay 1 (East)HM, Curlew Bay 2 (West)HM, and Gates BayHM), and three low-mid marsh sites (tall form Spartina)Â as well (same names, except MM as a suffix).Â  About 20 miles south, at the northÂ end of the Mockhorn Island WildlifeÂ Management Area (state owned), only two low-mid marsh sites were selected - Mockhorn East and West.Â Â The dataset does not include elevations taken at unvegetated pond sites as measurements were curtailed after 2003.Â

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

Current data collection method is to sample the SET sites each spring (late April to early June) and take measurements using the original SET arm at all sites.Â  Current use is with fiberglass pins, which replaced the brass pins of the late 1990s.Â  Sampling is best done at mid to low tides to ensure that the marsh site is not inundated.Â  For access to the sampling point, we use two 8-ft boards and one 10 ft board to provide access for two people to the SET.Â  One person does the measurements, the other records the data on field sheets or field notebook.Â

After the plate is leveled at each of 4 cardinal locations at the SET, the 9 pins are lowered until they just make contact with the marsh surface. Each pin is measured from the plate surface to the top of the pin using a meter stick. Data are recordedÂ to the nearest tenth of a centimeter.
Detailed instructions on data collection and recording from Mike Erwin sent to David Boyd on 2012-06-01:

1. First, we are down to only the four SETs at Wachapreague, labeled CB1E (Curlew Bay East) with a HM high marsh, and a MM mid marsh SET; also the CB2W (Curlew Bay West) - also a HM and a MM SET. At Mockhorn Island WMA, there are two: we have a Mock-E and a Mock-W both of which are considered mid marsh. Gates Bay SET sites were abandoned as we have anomalous readings there.

2. Take one reading per SET in the spring, from late April to late May advised. Low or mid tide levels will ensure that no water is standing at the SETs when you take measurements. Low tide is critical at the CB sites for the mid marsh SETs.
3. Upon approaching each SET from the creek side, avoid stepping within a radius of 4-5 ft. of where the pipe is located.
4. After placing the three boards, place the SET arm in the slots such that the arm position is at the 900 position first, which is the A position. The 1200 position is B, 300 is C, and 600 is D.

5. Make sure the arm is level first before pins are dropped. 6. Lower each pin until it BARELY touches the sediment surface. 7. With meter stick, measure FROM THE PLATE to the top of the pin, recording in tenths of centimeters on the data sheets. 8. After returning to the office, calculate the means for each SET (N=36 pins) and record in the SET master file (Erwin SET file).

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

In the 1.0 acre and 100,000 seed plots (n = 4), plant productivity was measured on all shoots within a 20 cm x 10 cm anchored grid using the leaf marking method where the blades are punctured with a 22-gauge needle, using the top of the sheath bundle as the reference point. Shoots were collected 10-15 days after marking, and leaf area and dry weights of the older growth (above the scar) and the new growth (below the scar, but excluding the sheath bundle and including new shoots) were measured.

The flux tower site (37ÃÂ°24'39.85N, 75ÃÂ°50'0.53W) a lagoonal salt marsh which is located near the area of Fowling point. This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

The flux tower instrumentation includesÂ  an eddy covariance system and various micrometeorological sensors.Â  The eddy covariance system consists of a three dimensional sonic anemometer (model CSAT3, Campbell Scientific Inc, Logan UT, USA), which measures the components of the wind velocity in the x, y, and z directions along with virtual temperature and an open path gas analyzer (model LI-7500, Licor Inc, Lincoln, NE, USA) which measures
the concentration of CO2 and H2O in the air. These measurements were used to estimate the fluxes of carbon dioxide, latent heat, and sensible heat.Â

The construction methodologies were adopted from the previous work of Barr (2005), who described the construction of a flux towerÂ  located at a riverine mangrove forest in the western Florida Everglades.Â  The tower base consists of two platforms, one for the aluminum tower base and the other for the battery bank and electronics. The tower base and the battery platform are 0.61 m and 1.4 m high from the sediment surface, respectively. The platforms are constructed on 11 wooden pilings (4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢x4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢) pressure treated lumber that were sunk into the sediment to a suitable depth for stability (~1.5 m). To ensure equal weight distribution on all 11 tiers and to prevent tiers from settling, pressure treated foundation beams (2x8Ã¢â¬) were bolted to the pilings using galvanized 7xÃÂ½ carriage bolts. Scrap boards of 2x12 treated lumber

were installed around the base of vertical tiers; these planks rest flat on the sediment and provide extra surface area toÂ  prevent foundation beams from sinking. The floor of the tower base and the ancillary platform were constructed with 2Ã¢â¬x8Ã¢â¬ pressure treated planks, which rest on floor beams made up of 2Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ x 4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ pressure treated lumber.
The flux tower was constructed using pre-fabricated aluminum tower sections (Universal towers, Clinton Township, MI, USA). Each section is 3 m long, and two sections

were used in the tower construction giving aÂ  total height of 6.7 m from the soil sediment surface. The tower sections were mounted on an aluminum base (3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3/8Ã¢â¬â¢) that was bolted onto the main platform base. To maintain structural stability, the tower was anchored to the sediment surface using a set of three guy wires attached to the top of the tower. These guy wires were attached to wooden pilings on the ground through galvanized turnbuckles (Model 3000T566, McMaster-Carr, Atlanta, GA, USA). Although two tower sections do not require the use of guy wires, these wereÂ  added for extra stability as theÂ  tower may be exposed to high force winds.Â

LiDAR-based Digital Elevation Model for Northampton and Accomack Co., VA, 2010
Virginia Coast Reserve Long-Term Ecological Research Project
Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Virginia, 291 McCormick Road, PO Box 400123

This dataset contains a bare-earth digital elevation model (DEM) for Northampton and Accomack Counties, Virginia based on data collected March 25-30, 2010 and processed to yield bare-earth elevations.

It was created using LiDAR by Sanborne Geosystems under a contract with the Virginia Information Technologies Agency (VITA) with funding from The Nature Conservancy, USGS and the Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project of the University of Virginia.
Original LiDAR point data (approximately 1 meter spacing) was used to create a digital elevation model (DEM) with a cell resolution of 10 ft. (3.048 m).Â

The DEM data layer is in the State Plane coordinate system (U.S. Feet) and uses the NAVD88 vertical datum with the 2009 Geoid for elevation in feet. As detailed in the included quality report, elevations are accurate to 0.65 feet or better.

Water areas have been hydroflattened and may also include salt marsh areas that were inundated at the time of the flights. Â As a result, water areas were given a default minimum elevation below the minimum elevation measured by LiDAR over a given area and dependent on tidal cycle.Â  Areas at or below this minimum elevation within the water mask may include salt marsh and tidal flats as well as open water.Â  The elevation of the hydroflattening varies spatially.

Salt marsh areas within the water mask were later determined by VCRLTER staff based on the following factors: (1) present as marsh (code 18) in the NOAA CCAP 2006 land cover layer and not included as an open water feature in the 2010 USGS National Hydrography Dataset, (2) minimum contiguous area of 1800 square meters, approximately equal to two 30 meter resolution CCAP pixel cells, and (3) includes extensive areas of salt marsh within north-south flight line Ã¢â¬ÅstripesÃ¢â¬, primarily the seaside lagoons and marshes south of Parramore Island and the town of Wachapreague plus Chesapeake Bay marshes immediately north of Â Tangier Island (and excludes edge-only areas elsewhere).

Two polygon shapefiles have been added to this dataset: one shapefile shows the region-specific water masks and includes the elevation of the masks (in meters, not feet); the other shapefile shows areas of saltmarsh hidden within the water mask and includes a recommended replacement elevation (0.404 meters) based on the average above-water-mask LiDAR elevations of all CCAP-minus-NHD-water-determined marshes of all seaside marshes south of Chincoteague Inlet.Â  The two polygon shapefiles have been reprojected to the WGS84 UTM zone 18N coordinate system, and the NAVD88 vertical elevations converted from feet to meters.

Sediment organic content was calculated as loss on ignition from sediment dry weight after combustion in a 500 ÃÂºC muffle furnace for 8 h.

The floor of the tower base and the ancillary platform were constructed with 2Ã¢â¬x8Ã¢â¬ pressure treated planks, which rest on floor beams made up of 2Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ x 4Ã¢â¬â¢Ã¢â¬â¢ pressure treated lumber.
The flux tower was constructed using pre-fabricated aluminum tower sections (Universal towers, Clinton Township, MI, USA). Each section is 3 m long, and two sections

were used in the tower construction giving aÂ  total height of 6.7 m from the soil sediment surface. The tower sections were mounted on an aluminum base (3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3Ã¢â¬â¢ x 3/8Ã¢â¬â¢) that was bolted onto the main platform base. To maintain structural stability, the tower was anchored to the sediment surface using a set of three guy wires attached to the top of the tower. These guy wires were attached to wooden pilings on the ground through galvanized turnbuckles (Model 3000T566, McMaster-Carr, Atlanta, GA, USA). Although two tower sections do not require the use of guy wires, these wereÂ  added for extra stability as theÂ  tower may be exposed to high force winds.Â

Zip files contain ESRI shapefiles. The name of the file identifies the parameter contained in the file and the year. Dhigh files have the most seaward dune crest. Dlow files have the most seaward dune toe. Shoreline position is mean-high water (0.34 m > mean-sea level).Additionally, the KML.zip file contains graphical representation of overwash probabilities for specific island-year combinations for display in Google Earth.

Shoreline location in 1997 of mean high water (MHW) which is 0.34m above sea level by Virginia standards. The shoreline points were derived from the 1997 lidar data. All shoreline points were selected from lidar data that was gridded and smoothed into cross-shore profiles every 10m alongshore. The grids are broken up into segments alongshore of similar shoreline orientation. To view the segments open the VA_segments shapefile. With in each segment the cross-shore profiles every 10 m were named profile 1, profile 2, profile 3, etc. That profile value is reflected in the attribute table in the column labeled 'profile'. The lat and lon of each shoreline point is represented as well as northing and easting. The position of the shoreline is presented in a few columns. The cross-shore position of the shoreline is called 'xsl' which refers to meters inland from the position 0. The 0 position is located between the two segment points (VA_segments).

Polygon of overwash probability during a hypothetical storm with characteristics similar to Hurricane Bonnie in 1998. The bar to the west is the probability of overwash for the VCR based on 1998 lidar data. The middle bar is the 2005 overwash probability based on the 2005 lidar data. And the most east bar is the 2009 overwash probability to the hypothetical storm. The storm surge used was 1.1m, the significant water wave height was 3.7m and the period was 7s. The probability is in part determined by comparing the relative elevation of the most seaward dune crest (Dhigh) and the maximum wave runup (Rhigh). Dhigh elevations are given in the attribute table. Each elevation value is a mean value representing 100m alongshore. The elevation of the most seaward dune toe (Dlow) also represents mean dlow elevation along the same 100m. R2 is the 2% exceedence elevation the swash will reach during the hypothetical storm. That elevation is added to the surge (1.1m) to equal Rhigh. Then the probability is represented as a % of overwash probability for each 100m segment of beach.

Google Earth (KML) files containing coded bands representing overwash probabilities on Cedar, Cobb, Hog, Myrtle, Parramore, Shipshoal, Smith and Wreck Islands for different 1998, 2005 and 2009, along with a legend graphic.

Five surface sediment samples were collected in each plot to a depth of 1 cm for analysis of benthic chlorophyll. Collected were kept in the dark on ice until they were frozen at -80 oC immediately after returning to the laboratory. Samples were later thawed and extracted in a 45:45 methanol:acetone solution overnight in the freezer after a 1-minute sonication. Benthic chlorophyll was determined spectrophotometrically using the equations of Lorenzen (1967).

The cross-shore position of the shoreline is called 'xsl' which refers to meters inland from the position 0. The 0 position is located between the two segment points (VA_segments).

Shoreline location in 2009 of mean high water (MHW) which is 0.34m above sea level by Virginia standards. The shoreline points were derived from the 2009 lidar data. Polygon of overwash probability during a hypothetical storm with characteristics similar to Hurricane Bonnie in 1998. The bar to the west is the probability of overwash for the VCR based on 1998 lidar data. The middle bar is the 2005 overwash probability based on the 2005 lidar data. And the most east bar is the 2009 overwash probability to the hypothetical storm. The storm surge used was 1.1m, the significant water wave height was 3.7m and the period was 7s. The probability is in part determined by comparing the relative elevation of the most seaward dune crest (Dhigh) and the maximum wave runup (Rhigh). Dhigh elevations are given in the attribute table. Each elevation value is a mean value representing 100m alongshore. The elevation of the most seaward dune toe (Dlow) also represents mean dlow elevation along the same 100m. R2 is the 2% exceedence elevation the swash will reach during the hypothetical storm. That elevation is added to the surge (1.1m) to equal Rhigh. Then the probability is represented as a % of overwash probability for each 100m segment of beach.

Google Earth (KML) files containing coded bands representing overwash probabilities on Cedar, Cobb, Hog, Myrtle, Parramore, Shipshoal, Smith and Wreck Islands for different 1998, 2005 and 2009, along with a legend graphic.

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

Five surface sediment samples were collected in each plot to a depth of 1 cm for analysis of benthic chlorophyll. Collected were kept in the dark on ice until they were frozen at -80 oC immediately after returning to the laboratory. Samples were later thawed and extracted in a 45:45 methanol:acetone solution overnight in the freezer after a 1-minute sonication. Benthic chlorophyll was determined spectrophotometrically using the equations of Lorenzen (1967).

This dataset contains information on water level and temperature in a series of groundwater wells in Phillips Creek Marsh, near Nassawadox, VA on the Eastern Shore of Virginia. Data on temperature and water pressure are collected every 12 minutes using automated Ceradiver data loggers and transformed following atmospheric adjustment into water levels. This dataset extends previous measurements using different technologies for three of the wells included in dataset: Ground Water Level at Brownsville and Hog Island, VA 1997-2009 (knb-lter-vcr.142). The Creekbank (CB), High Marsh (BH) and Tracy2 sites are the CB1, JUNCUS2 and BW3 sites in this dataset, respectively.

Schlumberger Ceradiver pressure and temperature loggers are used for data collection. Data are transformed into a column-oriented format using a PYTHON program and derived data are calculated using the R statistical package.
Groundwater Levels at Phillips Creek Marsh, VA 2012-present
Well CB1 (formerly CreekBank) - on bank of tidal creek
Well Juncus2 (formerly well BH) in high marsh
Reference barometer for adjusting well pressure sensors. Not in a well.
Date and time of water level measurement
MEASUREDATE - Date and time of water level measurement
Date and time of water level measurement
SERIALNO - Serial number of sensor used
Serial number of CeraDiver sensor used.
Note for barometric pressure sensor this is air temperature inside a closed container exposed to the sun.
Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer
Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.
Water depth relative to mean sea level
WATERMSL - Water depth relative to mean sea level

Wells were surveyed in using GPS and optical levels relative to NAVD-88 which is assumed to approximate mean sea level for this marsh. If no level information is available for a well, this value will be set to missing.
Depth of water relative to the marsh surface
WATERSURFACE - Depth of water relative to the marsh surface
PRESFLAG - Water pressure data quality flag
Range error detected. Range is outside the expected range of values

Spikes are single values that exceed the preceding and following values by 30 millibars or more. Valid pressure ranges are considered to fall between 860 and 1500 millibar. If a flag is set, no derived variables will be calculated based on the pressure.

Spikes are rapid increases or decreases in temperature that are more than 10 degrees C. Valid ranges for temperatures are between -35 degrees Celsius and 45 degrees Celsius. Note that the temperature of the reference barometer may exceed these values due to its location in a closed box exposed to the sun.

This dataset contains LiDAR data for Northampton and Accomack Counties on the Eastern Shore of Virginia.

It was created using LiDAR by Sanborn Geosystems under a contract with the Virginia Information Technologies Agency (VITA) with funding from The Nature Conservancy, USGS and the Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project of the University of Virginia.

The LiDAR data is stored in .LAS files with 4 returns per point. Spacing between points is approximately 1 meter. Returns are classified as to whether they are water or land. Each LAS file represents an area 5,000x5,000 feet. A tile index to aid in the identification of which LAS files are needed for a site are also included.
The data are is in the State Plane coordinate system (U.S. Feet) and uses the NAVD88 vertical datum with the 2009 Geoid for elevation in feet.

An IQEYE-3 webcam was used to capture the images which were then transferred for archiving using a wireless network. Each image is 1.3 megapixels.The camera was housed in a PELCO external camera case atop a 4x4 wooden post. Elevation of the top of the post above ground surface was variable, not because the post moved, but because the surrounding surface was raised by overwash.
Images were captured approximately every 10 seconds throughout the day. Some variability in timing resulted from delays in the wireless network, so timing is not exact.Â

Images are stored in a .tar file that includes a separate subdirectories containing images for each individual day. Images are stored as JPEG (.jpg) files and are labeled by name with the date and time of collection. Additionally, the images themselves contain a time stamp in the upper left corner. Note: This is a large file - over 50 GB.Â  Directories have the format: birds_cpole_YY_MM_DD where YY is the two-digit year (10 or 11), MM is the month number and DD is the day number. Image files have the format: Bird_DOW_MMM_DD_YYYY_HH_mm_SS_02e50.jpg where DOW is a 3-letter abbreviated Day-of-the-Week, MMM is a three letter month abbreviation, DD is the day number within the month, YYYY is the 4-digit year, HH is the hour, mm is the minute, and SS is the second. Additional characters (e.g. 02e50) deal with image numbers within a given second, but that is not needed here because only one image per 10 seconds was recorded.

This dataset contains information on water level and temperature in a series of groundwater wells in Phillips Creek Marsh, near Nassawadox, VA on the Eastern Shore of Virginia. Data on temperature and water pressure are collected every 12 minutes using automated Ceradiver data loggers and transformed following atmospheric adjustment into water levels. This dataset extends previous measurements using different technologies for three of the wells included in dataset: Ground Water Level at Brownsville and Hog Island, VA 1997-2009 (knb-lter-vcr.142). The Creekbank (CB), High Marsh (BH) and Tracy2 sites are the CB1, JUNCUS2 and BW3 sites in this dataset, respectively.

Schlumberger Ceradiver pressure and temperature loggers are used for data collection. Data are transformed into a column-oriented format using a PYTHON program and derived data are calculated using the R statistical package.
Groundwater Levels at Phillips Creek Marsh, VA 2012-present
Well CB1 (formerly CreekBank) - on bank of tidal creek
Well Juncus2 (formerly well BH) in high marsh
Reference barometer for adjusting well pressure sensors. Not in a well.
Date and time of water level measurement
MEASUREDATE - Date and time of water level measurement
Date and time of water level measurement
SERIALNO - Serial number of sensor used
Serial number of CeraDiver sensor used.
Note for barometric pressure sensor this is air temperature inside a closed container exposed to the sun.
Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer
Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.
Water depth relative to mean sea level
WATERMSL - Water depth relative to mean sea level

Wells were surveyed in using GPS and optical levels relative to NAVD-88 which is assumed to approximate mean sea level for this marsh. If no level information is available for a well, this value will be set to missing.
Depth of water relative to the marsh surface
WATERSURFACE - Depth of water relative to the marsh surface
PRESFLAG - Water pressure data quality flag
Range error detected. Range is outside the expected range of values

Spikes are single values that exceed the preceding and following values by 30 millibars or more. Valid pressure ranges are considered to fall between 860 and 1500 millibar. If a flag is set, no derived variables will be calculated based on the pressure.

Spikes are rapid increases or decreases in temperature that are more than 10 degrees C. Valid ranges for temperatures are between -35 degrees Celsius and 45 degrees Celsius. Note that the temperature of the reference barometer may exceed these values due to its location in a closed box exposed to the sun.

Sediments were collected in 60 cc syringe corers to a depth of 5 cm in each vegetated and bare plot for determination of sediment organic content, carbon and nitrogen contents, and grain size distribution. Five sediment cores were collected in each plot for each analysis; the reported values represent the integrated measure for the 0-5 cm depth interval. Sediment organic content was calculated as loss on ignition from sediment dry weight after combustion in a 500 ÃÂºC muffle furnace for 8 h.

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

In the 1.0 acre and 100,000 seed plots (n = 4), plant productivity was measured on all shoots within a 20 cm x 10 cm anchored grid using the leaf marking method where the blades are punctured with a 22-gauge needle, using the top of the sheath bundle as the reference point. Shoots were collected 10-15 days after marking, and leaf area and dry weights of the older growth (above the scar) and the new growth (below the scar, but excluding the sheath bundle and including new shoots) were measured.

Schlumberger Ceradiver pressure and temperature loggers are used for data collection. Data are transformed into a column-oriented format using a PYTHON program and derived data are calculated using the R statistical package.

Date and time of water level measurement
MEASUREDATE - Date and time of water level measurement
Date and time of water level measurement
SERIALNO - Serial number of sensor used
Serial number of CeraDiver sensor used.
Note for barometric pressure sensor this is air temperature inside a closed container exposed to the sun.
Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer
Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.
Water depth relative to mean sea level
WATERMSL - Water depth relative to mean sea level

Wells were surveyed in using GPS and optical levels relative to NAVD-88 which is assumed to approximate mean sea level for this marsh. If no level information is available for a well, this value will be set to missing.

PRESFLAG - Water pressure data quality flag
Range error detected. Range is outside the expected range of values

Spikes are single values that exceed the preceding and following values by 30 millibars or more. Valid pressure ranges are considered to fall between 860 and 1500 millibar. If a flag is set, no derived variables will be calculated based on the pressure.

Spikes are rapid increases or decreases in temperature that are more than 10 degrees C. Valid ranges for temperatures are between -35 degrees Celsius and 45 degrees Celsius. Note that the temperature of the reference barometer may exceed these values due to its location in a closed box exposed to the sun.

LiDAR point cloud for Northampton and Accomack Co., VA 2010
Virginia Coast Reserve Long-Term Ecological Research Project
Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Virginia, 291 McCormick Road, PO Box 400123
This dataset contains LiDAR data for Northampton and Accomack Counties on the Eastern Shore of Virginia.

It was created using LiDAR by Sanborn Geosystems under a contract with the Virginia Information Technologies Agency (VITA) with funding from The Nature Conservancy, USGS and the Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project of the University of Virginia.

The LiDAR data is stored in .LAS files with 4 returns per point. Spacing between points is approximately 1 meter. Returns are classified as to whether they are water or land. Each LAS file represents an area 5,000x5,000 feet. A tile index to aid in the identification of which LAS files are needed for a site are also included.
The data are is in the State Plane coordinate system (U.S. Feet) and uses the NAVD88 vertical datum with the 2009 Geoid for elevation in feet.

This dataset contains images used to observe double-crested cormorant and great egret nests on Chimney Pole Marsh, VA, a low-lying barrier marsh on the Atlantic coast of the Delmarva Peninsula.
The camera was in operation June 15, 2010 to July 7, 2010, Aug, 3, 4 and 31, 2010, and May 10 through Aug. 11, 2011.
Images were captured roughly once every 10 seconds during the day, resulting in a total of 287,564 images.

An IQEYE-3 webcam was used to capture the images which were then transferred for archiving using a wireless network. Each image is 1.3 megapixels.The camera was housed in a PELCO external camera case atop a 4x4 wooden post. Elevation of the top of the post above ground surface was variable, not because the post moved, but because the surrounding surface was raised by overwash.
Images were captured approximately every 10 seconds throughout the day. Some variability in timing resulted from delays in the wireless network, so timing is not exact.Â

Images are stored in a .tar file that includes a separate subdirectories containing images for each individual day. Images are stored as JPEG (.jpg) files and are labeled by name with the date and time of collection. Additionally, the images themselves contain a time stamp in the upper left corner. Note: This is a large file - over 50 GB.Â  Directories have the format: birds_cpole_YY_MM_DD where YY is the two-digit year (10 or 11), MM is the month number and DD is the day number. Image files have the format: Bird_DOW_MMM_DD_YYYY_HH_mm_SS_02e50.jpg where DOW is a 3-letter abbreviated Day-of-the-Week, MMM is a three letter month abbreviation, DD is the day number within the month, YYYY is the 4-digit year, HH is the hour, mm is the minute, and SS is the second. Additional characters (e.g. 02e50) deal with image numbers within a given second, but that is not needed here because only one image per 10 seconds was recorded.

The Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project, in association with the Virginia Marine Resources Commission, conducted an intensive GPS survey during February 1992. A second GPS survey was conducted in August 1994 to add supplemental GPS monuments. Most monuments consist of stainless steel pipes driven to refusal and topped with a bolt with a point imprinted on it. Others may consist of existing markers or cultural features. Elevations refer to the monument, not the surrounding ground surface. All data were processed by the VCR/LTER. Several caveats must be applied to use of this survey network:
1. These are preliminary results and are subject to change as the network is revised.
2. This network is designed for research purposes only, the data are not suitable for legal uses of survey data.

3. The network includes several US Government benchmarks, but except for the VCR1 monument recently resurveyed and fixed by the National Geodetic Survey (see below), the coordinates for those benchmarks have not been adjusted to agree with blue-book values for those benchmarks.
4. Elevations are based on mean sea-level (NAVD88) for a single point (VCR1). No geoid corrections have been applied to any other point.

Most data were collected using dual-frequency Trimble 4000 GPS units and additional data was collected with single-frequency GPS units. All measurements were made using the WGS84 datum. Each location was measured a minimum of two times with data collection times greater than 3 hours per survey.
1. Data were processed using TRIMVEC+ software.
2. Baselines were computed using widelane fixed solutions whenever possible. If a quality ratio <3 could not be obtained, a float solution was used instead.
3. A network made up of only the highest quality baselines (fixed) solutions was created and fixed based on the geographical coordinates and elevation of the VCR1 monument.

4. A network comprised of all points was compiled. As before, the coordinates for VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) were fixed in 3 dimensions. The stations BROWNSVILLE, FARL and SHUG were fixed to their horizontal coordinates in the high-quality-only network. Network adjustments were then performed on all other points.
NGS location of VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) monument. The VCR1 monument is part of the High Accuracy and Resolution Network (HARN).

5/3/94 - National Geodetic Survey fixes the VCR1 monument at 37-deg, 17-min, 42.15663-seconds North Latitude and 75-deg, 55-min, 59.49256-sec. West Longitude, with an ellipsoidal height of -28.261 m. Geoid height is modeled to be 8.7 m. Horizontal datum is NAD 83 and vertical datum is NAVD 88 (for NGVD 29, add 0.2 m).

This dataset contains information on water level and temperature in a series of groundwater wells in Phillips Creek Marsh, near Nassawadox, VA on the Eastern Shore of Virginia. Data on temperature and water pressure are collected every 12 minutes using automated Ceradiver data loggers and transformed following atmospheric adjustment into water levels. This dataset extends previous measurements using different technologies for three of the wells included in dataset: Ground Water Level at Brownsville and Hog Island, VA 1997-2009 (knb-lter-vcr.142). The Creekbank (CB), High Marsh (BH) and Tracy2 sites are the CB1, JUNCUS2 and BW3 sites in this dataset, respectively.

Note for barometric pressure sensor this is air temperature inside a closed container exposed to the sun.
Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer
Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.
Water depth relative to mean sea level
WATERMSL - Water depth relative to mean sea level

Wells were surveyed in using GPS and optical levels relative to NAVD-88 which is assumed to approximate mean sea level for this marsh. If no level information is available for a well, this value will be set to missing.

PRESFLAG - Water pressure data quality flag

Spikes are single values that exceed the preceding and following values by 30 millibars or more. Valid pressure ranges are considered to fall between 860 and 1500 millibar. If a flag is set, no derived variables will be calculated based on the pressure.

Spikes are rapid increases or decreases in temperature that are more than 10 degrees C. Valid ranges for temperatures are between -35 degrees Celsius and 45 degrees Celsius. Note that the temperature of the reference barometer may exceed these values due to its location in a closed box exposed to the sun.

This section contains specific methods for this dataset.

For biomass estimates, three cores (6Ã¢â¬ I.D.) containing shoots were collected, including sediment and seagrass biomass to 15 cm depth, in each plot. The cores were sieved (1 cm mesh size) in situ to remove sediments. In the laboratory, shoots were separated into aboveground and belowground biomass for each core, and the number of shoots was counted to obtain estimates of total, above- and belowground biomass shoot-1. Canopy height was determined as the average height of the 3 tallest leaves.

This dataset contains LiDAR data for Northampton and Accomack Counties on the Eastern Shore of Virginia.

It was created using LiDAR by Sanborn Geosystems under a contract with the Virginia Information Technologies Agency (VITA) with funding from The Nature Conservancy, USGS and the Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project of the University of Virginia.

The LiDAR data is stored in .LAS files with 4 returns per point. Spacing between points is approximately 1 meter. Returns are classified as to whether they are water or land. Each LAS file represents an area 5,000x5,000 feet. A tile index to aid in the identification of which LAS files are needed for a site are also included.
The data are is in the State Plane coordinate system (U.S. Feet) and uses the NAVD88 vertical datum with the 2009 Geoid for elevation in feet.

This dataset contains information on water level and temperature in a series of groundwater wells in Phillips Creek Marsh, near Nassawadox, VA on the Eastern Shore of Virginia. Data on temperature and water pressure are collected every 12 minutes using automated Ceradiver data loggers and transformed following atmospheric adjustment into water levels. This dataset extends previous measurements using different technologies for three of the wells included in dataset: Ground Water Level at Brownsville and Hog Island, VA 1997-2009 (knb-lter-vcr.142). The Creekbank (CB), High Marsh (BH) and Tracy2 sites are the CB1, JUNCUS2 and BW3 sites in this dataset, respectively.

The Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project, in association with the Virginia Marine Resources Commission, conducted an intensive GPS survey during February 1992. A second GPS survey was conducted in August 1994 to add supplemental GPS monuments. Most monuments consist of stainless steel pipes driven to refusal and topped with a bolt with a point imprinted on it. Others may consist of existing markers or cultural features. Elevations refer to the monument, not the surrounding ground surface. All data were processed by the VCR/LTER. Several caveats must be applied to use of this survey network:
1. These are preliminary results and are subject to change as the network is revised.
2. This network is designed for research purposes only, the data are not suitable for legal uses of survey data.

3. The network includes several US Government benchmarks, but except for the VCR1 monument recently resurveyed and fixed by the National Geodetic Survey (see below), the coordinates for those benchmarks have not been adjusted to agree with blue-book values for those benchmarks.
4. Elevations are based on mean sea-level (NAVD88) for a single point (VCR1). No geoid corrections have been applied to any other point.

Update: Â  MINOR coordinate shifts resulting from NGS adjustment of the VCR1 monument's estimated lat/lon following the NAD83 (Va) HARN adjustment of 2011 have been calculated (0.017 m S, 0.001 m W), but not otherwise applied to the data.Â  A shapefile of the VCR GPS network based on the original coordinates has also been included.

Most data were collected using dual-frequency Trimble 4000 GPS units and additional data was collected with single-frequency GPS units. All measurements were made using the WGS84 datum. Each location was measured a minimum of two times with data collection times greater than 3 hours per survey.
1. Data were processed using TRIMVEC+ software.
2. Baselines were computed using widelane fixed solutions whenever possible. If a quality ratio <3 could not be obtained, a float solution was used instead.
3. A network made up of only the highest quality baselines (fixed) solutions was created and fixed based on the geographical coordinates and elevation of the VCR1 monument.

4. A network comprised of all points was compiled. As before, the coordinates for VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) were fixed in 3 dimensions. The stations BROWNSVILLE, FARL and SHUG were fixed to their horizontal coordinates in the high-quality-only network. Network adjustments were then performed on all other points.
NGS location of VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) monument. The VCR1 monument is part of the High Accuracy and Resolution Network (HARN).

5/3/94 - National Geodetic Survey fixes the VCR1 monument at 37-deg, 17-min, 42.15663-seconds North Latitude and 75-deg, 55-min, 59.49256-sec. West Longitude, with an ellipsoidal height of -28.261 m. Geoid height is modeled to be 8.7 m. Horizontal datum is NAD 83 and vertical datum is NAVD 88 (for NGVD 29, add 0.2 m).

(2013) Additional adjustment information and UTM coordinates for dataset VCR12197: âGPS Survey Monuments on the Virginia Coast Reserve 1992-1994â. NGS has made very minor adjustments since 1993 to the horizontal coordinates associated with VCR1 monument. The original (1993) latitude/longitude coordinates relative to the NAD1983 VA HARN adjustment of 1993 datum are provided in the attribute data, as are the newer (2011) latitude/longitude coordinates relative to the NAD1983 VA HARN adjustment of 2011 datum . Also provided are UTM coordinates for each monument obtained by transforming both the original and newer lat/lon coordinates into NAD83- and WGS84-based UTM zone 18N coordinates. No adjustments to the vertical elevation datum have yet occurred; all elevations are relative to the North American Vertical Datum of 1988 (NAVD88).

In each plot, Zostera marina shoot density was determined by counting individual shoots in situ in 10 0.25 m2 quadrats, and scaling to shoot density m-2. Quadrats were placed at a random distance perpendicular to the transect line at each sampling point.

The Virginia Coast Reserve Long-term Ecological Research project, in association with the Virginia Marine Resources Commission, conducted an intensive GPS survey during February 1992. A second GPS survey was conducted in August 1994 to add supplemental GPS monuments. Most monuments consist of stainless steel pipes driven to refusal and topped with a bolt with a point imprinted on it. Others may consist of existing markers or cultural features. Elevations refer to the monument, not the surrounding ground surface. All data were processed by the VCR/LTER. Several caveats must be applied to use of this survey network:
1. These are preliminary results and are subject to change as the network is revised.
2. This network is designed for research purposes only, the data are not suitable for legal uses of survey data.

3. The network includes several US Government benchmarks, but except for the VCR1 monument recently resurveyed and fixed by the National Geodetic Survey (see below), the coordinates for those benchmarks have not been adjusted to agree with blue-book values for those benchmarks.
4. Elevations are based on mean sea-level (NAVD88) for a single point (VCR1). No geoid corrections have been applied to any other point.

Most data were collected using dual-frequency Trimble 4000 GPS units and additional data was collected with single-frequency GPS units. All measurements were made using the WGS84 datum. Each location was measured a minimum of two times with data collection times greater than 3 hours per survey.
1. Data were processed using TRIMVEC+ software.
2. Baselines were computed using widelane fixed solutions whenever possible. If a quality ratio <3 could not be obtained, a float solution was used instead.
3. A network made up of only the highest quality baselines (fixed) solutions was created and fixed based on the geographical coordinates and elevation of the VCR1 monument.

4. A network comprised of all points was compiled. As before, the coordinates for VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) were fixed in 3 dimensions. The stations BROWNSVILLE, FARL and SHUG were fixed to their horizontal coordinates in the high-quality-only network. Network adjustments were then performed on all other points.
NGS location of VCR1 (VCR LTER 1) monument. The VCR1 monument is part of the High Accuracy and Resolution Network (HARN).

5/3/94 - National Geodetic Survey fixes the VCR1 monument at 37-deg, 17-min, 42.15663-seconds North Latitude and 75-deg, 55-min, 59.49256-sec. West Longitude, with an ellipsoidal height of -28.261 m. Geoid height is modeled to be 8.7 m. Horizontal datum is NAD 83 and vertical datum is NAVD 88 (for NGVD 29, add 0.2 m).

NGS has made very minor adjustments since 1993 to the horizontal coordinates associated with VCR1 monument. The original (1993) latitude/longitude coordinates relative to the NAD1983 VA HARN adjustment of 1993 datum are provided in the attribute data, as are the newer (2011) latitude/longitude coordinates relative to the NAD1983 VA HARN adjustment of 2011 datum . Also provided are UTM coordinates for each monument obtained by transforming both the original and newer lat/lon coordinates into NAD83- and WGS84-based UTM zone 18N coordinates. No adjustments to the vertical elevation datum have yet occurred; all elevations are relative to the North American Vertical Datum of 1988 (NAVD88).

This dataset contains information on water level and temperature in a series of groundwater wells in Phillips Creek Marsh, near Nassawadox, VA on the Eastern Shore of Virginia. Data on temperature and water pressure are collected every 12 minutes using automated Ceradiver data loggers and transformed following atmospheric adjustment into water levels. This dataset extends previous measurements using different technologies for three of the wells included in dataset: Ground Water Level at Brownsville and Hog Island, VA 1997-2009 (knb-lter-vcr.142). The Creekbank (CB), High Marsh (BH) and Tracy2 sites are the CB1, JUNCUS2 and BW3 sites in this dataset, respectively.

Schlumberger Ceradiver pressure and temperature loggers are used for data collection. Data are transformed into a column-oriented format using a PYTHON program and derived data are calculated using the R statistical package.

Note for barometric pressure sensor this is air temperature inside a closed container exposed to the sun.
Water pressure + air pressure are measured by the submerged CeraDiver pressure sensor. To get water pressure, alone, air pressure must be subtracted based on a reference barometer.
AIRPRESSURE - Air pressure at reference barometer
Air pressure at the reference barometer is collected every 12-min to 1 hour and interpolated to the time of collection using a linear algorithm.
Assuming fresh water, water depth equals one centimeter of depth for each millibar of pressure. For salt water, this is an overestimate of the water depth by 1.06.
